{{Infobox Monument |monument_name = Sir George-Étienne Cartier Monument |native_name = |image = Montreal - Parc Mont-Royal, Statue d'Athéna - 20050320.jpg |caption = [[Liberty (goddess)|Liberty]] backlit by the Sun |location = [[Mount Royal Park]] |designer = [[George William Hill (sculptor)|George William Hill]] |type = Historical Monument |material = Bronze, Stanstead granite |length = |width = {{convert|8.75|m|ft}} |height = {{convert|30.78|m|ft}} |begin = 1913 |complete = 1919 |open = September 6, 1919 |dedicated_to = [[George-Étienne Cartier]] |map_image = |map_caption = |map_width = |coordinates = {{Coord|45.514226|-73.585262|format=dms|display=title}} |lat = |long = |extra = }} [[File:Sir_George_Etienne_Cartier_Monument,_Montreal.jpg|thumb|The George-Étienne Cartier Monument in Mount Royal Park, Montreal]] The '''Sir George-Étienne Cartier Monument''' is a monument in [[Mount Royal#Mount Royal Park|Mount Royal Park]] to [[George-Étienne Cartier]] by sculptor [[George William Hill (sculptor)|George William Hill]] (1862–1934). [[File:Monument G E Cartier Est.JPG|thumb|left|The ''George-Étienne Cartier'' statue on the monument]] The monument, which is topped by a winged [[Liberty (goddess)|Goddess of Liberty]], was inaugurated on September 6, 1919 in the heart of Fletcher's Field west side. In temperate months it is the site of free weekly drum circle festivals informally called [[Tam-Tams]].<ref name="cartier">{{cite news|url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=9d571f9c-ad2e-44f0-b106-138ef2ea32a3|title=Cartier returns|date=May 23, 2008|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|accessdate=31 March 2010}}</ref>
On the front, or East side of the monument, George-Étienne Cartier is portrayed standing above four other figures, each one representing a Province that signed the [[Canadian Confederation|Canadian Confederation of 1867]].
On the North side of the monument, a woman with a young girl to her right and a young boy to her left is shown holding a sword in her left hand. The boy holds out his bonded wrists in a begging manner as the girl reads a book. This scene represents [[Canadian legislation|Legislation]].
On the South side, in a similar scene to the North side, a woman sits in the middle of a young boy who is holding a ball and a young girl who is reading a book. This represents Cartier's important contributions in education.
