{{Feminism sidebar |Variants (general)}} {{Individualism sidebar}} {{Libertarianism sidebar}}
'''Individualist feminism''', sometimes also grouped with '''libertarian feminism''', is [[Feminism|feminist]] ideas which emphasize [[individualism]].<ref name="About_ALF">{{cite web | title = About ALF - The Association of Libertarian Feminists | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090828170220/http://alf.org/aboutalf/founding.shtml | archive-date = August 28, 2009 | url = http://alf.org/aboutalf/founding.shtml | website = alf.org | publisher = Association of Libertarian Feminists }}</ref>
== General ==
Individualist feminists attempt to change legal systems to eliminate class privileges and gender privileges and to ensure that individuals have equal rights, including an equal claim under the law to their own persons and property. Individualist feminism encourages women to take full responsibility for their own lives. It also opposes any government interference into the choices adults make with their own bodies because, it contends, such interference creates a coercive hierarchy (such as [[patriarchy]]).<ref>''Citations'': :* {{cite book | editor-last = McElroy | editor-first = Wendy|editor-link=Wendy McElroy | title = Liberty for women: freedom and feminism in the twenty-first century | publisher = Ivan R. Dee | location = Chicago | year = 2002 | isbn = 9781566634359 }} :* {{cite book | last = Kennedy Taylor | first = Joan | author-link = Joan Kennedy Taylor | title = Reclaiming the mainstream: individualist feminism rediscovered | publisher = Prometheus Books | location = Buffalo, N.Y | year = 1992 | isbn = 9780879757175 }} :* {{cite book | last = Kennedy Taylor | first = Joan | author-link = Joan Kennedy Taylor | title = What to do when you don't want to call the cops: a non-adversarial approach to sexual harassment | publisher = New York University Press | location = London New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780814782323 }}</ref> One central theme of individualist feminism revolves around the [[Free love|Free Love Movement]], which indicates that a woman's sexual choices should be made by her and her alone, rather than by government regulations.<ref>{{cite web|last=McElroy|first=Wendy|author-link=Wendy McElroy|title=Individualist Feminism: The Lost Tradition|url=https://fee.org/articles/individualist-feminism-the-lost-tradition|website=fee.org| publisher = [[Foundation for Economic Education]]|accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>
Individualist feminism was cast to appeal to "younger women ... of a more conservative generation"<ref name="SisterhoodInterrupt-123">{{cite book | last = Siegel | first = Deborah | chapter = Postfeminist panache | editor-last = Siegel | editor-first = Deborah | title = Sisterhood, interrupted: from radical women to grrls gone wild | pages = 123 and 122–124 & nn. 32–34 | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = New York | edition = 1st | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781403982049 }}</ref> and includes concepts from [[Rene Denfeld]] and [[Naomi Wolf]], essentially that "feminism should no longer be about communal solutions to communal problems but individual solutions to individual problems",<ref name="SisterhoodInterrupt-123" /> and concepts from [[Wendy McElroy]] and especially [[Joan Kennedy Taylor]].
The Association of Libertarian Feminists, founded in 1973 by [[Tonie Nathan]], the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party's]] [[Vice President of the United States|Vice Presidential]] nominee in [[United States presidential election, 1972|1972]], is one of a number of different kinds of individualist feminist organizations.<ref name="About_ALF" /> It takes a strong anti-government and pro-choice stand.<ref>{{cite web | last1 = Presley | first1 = Sharon | last2 = Kinsky | first2 = Lynn | author-link1 = Sharon Presley | title = ALF Paper - Government is Women's Enemy | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081226003724/http://alf.org/papers/gwe1.shtml | archive-date= December 26, 2008 | url = http://alf.org/papers/gwe1.shtml | website = alf.org | publisher = Association of Libertarian Feminists }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1 = Presley | first1 = Sharon | last2 = Cooke | first2 = Robert | author-link1 = Sharon Presley | title = ALF Paper - The Right to Abortion: A Libertarian Defense | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20081225235956/http://alf.org/papers/abortion.shtml |archive-date=December 25, 2008 | url = http://alf.org/papers/abortion.shtml | website = alf.org | publisher = Association of Libertarian Feminists}}</ref> Other [[libertarianism|libertarian]] feminist organizations include the [[Ladies of Liberty Alliance]],<ref>{{cite web | title = About us | url = http://ladiesofliberty.org/about-us/ | publisher = [[Ladies of Liberty Alliance]] | access-date = 1 January 2018}}</ref> Feminists for Liberty,<ref>{{cite web | title = About | url = https://feministsforliberty.com/about/ | publisher = Feminists for Liberty | access-date = 1 January 2018}}</ref> and the defunct Mother's Institute,<ref>{{cite web | title = About us | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120229085630/http://themothersinstitute.org/about.htm | archive-date = 29 February 2012 | url = http://themothersinstitute.org/about.htm | publisher = The Mother's Institute | access-date = 1 January 2018}}</ref> which included Mothers for Liberty (meet-up groups).<ref>{{cite web | title = Mothers for Liberty Meet-up Groups | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090522125207/http://www.themothersinstitute.org/mothersforliberty.htm | archive-date = 22 May 2009 | url = http://www.themothersinstitute.org/mothersforliberty.htm | publisher = The Mother's Institute | access-date = 1 January 2018}}</ref>
[[Wendy McElroy]] and [[Christina Hoff Sommers]] define individualist feminism in opposition to what they call ''political'' or ''[[gender feminism]]''.<ref name=mcelroy1>{{cite book | editor-last = McElroy | editor-first = Wendy|editor-link=Wendy McElroy | title = Liberty for women: freedom and feminism in the twenty-first century|page=14 | publisher = Ivan R. Dee | location = Chicago | year = 2002 | isbn = 9781566634359 }}</ref><ref name=Hoff_Sommers>{{cite book | last = Hoff Sommers | first = Christina |authorlink=Christina Hoff Sommers | title = [[Who Stole Feminism? How Women Have Betrayed Women]] | publisher = Touchstone/Simon & Schuster | location = New York | year = 1995 | isbn = 9780684801568 }}</ref>
