'''Vanessa Siddle Walker''' is the Samuel Candler Dobbs Professor of African American Educational Studies at [[Emory University]] and the president-elect of the [[American Educational Research Association]] (AERA).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aera.net/Newsroom/AERA-Highlights-E-newsletter/-em-AERA-Highlights-em-March-2018/Vanessa-Siddle-Walker-Voted-AERA-President-Elect|title=Vanessa Siddle Walker Voted AERA President-Elect; Key Members Elected to AERA Council|website=www.aera.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aera.net/Newsroom/Vanessa-Siddle-Walker-Voted-AERA-President-Elect|title=Vanessa Siddle Walker Voted AERA President-Elect|website=www.aera.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Walker has studied the segregation of the American educational system for twenty five years and published the non-fiction work: ''The Lost Education Of Horace Tate: Uncovering The Hidden Heroes Who Fought For Justice In Schools''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/bitchreads-july-2018-selections|title=11 Books Feminists Should Read In July|work=Bitch Media|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-1-620971-05-5|title=Nonfiction Book Review: The Lost Education of Horace Tate: Uncovering the Hidden Heroes Who Fought for Justice in Schools by Vanessa Siddle Walker. New Press, $32.99 (480p) ISBN 978-1-620971-05-5|work=PublishersWeekly.com|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-education-of-horace-tate-review-civil-rights-for-schoolchildren-1534892544|title=‘The Lost Education of Horace Tate’ Review: Civil Rights for Schoolchildren|last=Roth|first=Michael S.|date=2018-08-21|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-08-24|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> She has received the Grawmeyer Award for Education, the AERA Early Career Award,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aera.net/Newsroom/AERA-Highlights-E-newsletter/-em-AERA-Highlights-em-March-2018/Vanessa-Siddle-Walker-Voted-AERA-President-Elect|title=Vanessa Siddle Walker Voted AERA President-Elect; Key Members Elected to AERA Council|website=www.aera.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> the Conference of Southern Graduate Schools,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://naeducation.org/vanessa-siddle-walker/|title=Vanessa Siddle Walker - National Academy of Education|work=National Academy of Education|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en-US}}</ref> the American Education Studies Association,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.emory.edu/stories/2018/04/er_tn_walker_aera/campus.html|title=Emory professor Vanessa Siddle Walker voted American Educational Research Association president-elect|date=2018-04-09|website=news.emory.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> and three awards from AERA Divisions, including Best New Female Scholar, Best New Book, and Outstanding Book.
== Education == Walker received her B.A. from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, her M.Ed from Harvard University, and her Ed. D Harvard University.
== Publications == Walker’s book publications include Their Highest Potential: An African American School Community in the Segregated South (University of North Carolina Press),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Siddle|first=Walker, Vanessa|date=1996-00-00|title=Their Highest Potential: An African American School Community in the Segregated South.|url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED399328|language=en}}</ref> Facing Racism in Education (Harvard Educational Review Reprint Series),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hepg.org/hep-home/books/facing-racism-in-education|title=Facing Racism in Education|website=hepg.org|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> Racing Moral Formation (Teachers College Press),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tcpress.com/race-ing-moral-formation-9780807744499|title=Race-ing Moral Formation 9780807744499 {{!}} Teachers College Press|website=www.tcpress.com|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> and Hello Professor: A Black Principal and Professional Leadership in the Segregated South (University of North Carolina Press),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/10.5149/9780807888759_walker|title=Hello Professor: A Black Principal and Professional Leadership in the Segregated South|last=Walker|first=Vanessa Siddle|last2=Byas|first2=Ulysses|date=2009|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=9780807832899|doi=10.5149/9780807888759_walker}}</ref> and Living the Legacy: Universities and Schools in Collaborative for African American Children (Rowan and Little),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aas.emory.edu/home/people/spotlight/vanessa-walker.html|title=New Faculty Bio: Vanessa Siddell Walker|website=aas.emory.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref> The Lost Education of Horace Tate: Uncovering the hidden heroes who fought for justice in schools (The New Press).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thenewpress.com/books/lost-education-of-horace-tate|title=The Lost Education of Horace Tate {{!}} The New Press|work=The New Press|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref>
